    author: "Melanie Brown",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1477959858617-67f85cf4f1df?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>Pioneering physicist and inventor Nikola Tesla dreamt of connecting the world through wireless communication and power. Despite demonstrating he could transfer power over short distances, his longer-distance experiments were considerably less successful. But now — more than one hundred years after Tesla's demonstrations — his dream of wireless power is closer to becoming a reality than ever before.</p><p>In countries where rugged landscapes make laying traditional power lines difficult and costly, wireless electricity could help connect communities who are without mains power. The technology relies on electromagnetic resonance, where two coils tuned to the same frequency can exchange energy across a gap, much like how a tuning fork can make another fork vibrate across a room.</p><p>Startups around the world are developing 'beamable' electricity. In New Zealand, engineers have demonstrated an electric guitar being powered from 36 metres away with no wires, using focused microwave beams with laser safety curtains to protect any wildlife that might wander into the path.</p><p>Wireless electricity could also help fulfil the power demands of a growing electric vehicle market. In the town of Wenatchee, Washington, the local transit authority has been electrifying its bus fleet and embedding wireless chargers into the tarmac at bus stops so that buses can trickle-charge as passengers get on and off.</p><p>The implications extend into our homes too. Imagine a living room where your phone, laptop, speakers, and lamp all receive power through the air — no cables, no chargers, no tangled cords behind your desk. Resonant coupling technology is already making this possible at short range, and researchers believe room-scale wireless power could arrive within the decade.</p><p>The challenges remain significant: efficiency drops with distance, regulatory hurdles around microwave transmission need clearing, and public perception of 'beamed energy' requires careful management. But the trajectory is clear — Tesla's impossible dream is steadily becoming engineering reality.</p>"
