    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1446776811953-b23d57bd21aa?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>What if we could harvest solar energy where the sun never sets — in orbit — and beam it down to Earth? That's the promise of space-based solar power, a concept that's been on the drawing board since the 1960s but is now closer to reality than ever.</p><p>In 2023, Caltech's Space Solar Power Demonstrator successfully transmitted power wirelessly in space for the first time, proving that the fundamental physics works outside the laboratory. The demonstration used lightweight, flexible photovoltaic tiles and microwave transmitters to beam energy to a receiver.</p><p>The advantages are staggering. A solar panel in geostationary orbit receives sunlight 24 hours a day, 365 days a year, with no clouds, no night, and no atmosphere to filter the light. Calculations suggest orbital solar could deliver 40 times more energy per square metre than ground-based panels.</p><p>The energy would be transmitted to Earth as microwaves — at frequencies that pass harmlessly through clouds and rain — and collected by large ground-based antennas called rectennas. These could be built over farmland without disrupting agriculture, since the microwave beam would be too diffuse to affect crops or livestock.</p><p>The biggest obstacle remains cost. Launching the thousands of tonnes of hardware needed for a commercial-scale system is currently prohibitive, but falling launch costs from reusable rockets are changing the equation rapidly. Several national space agencies and private companies are now running serious feasibility studies.</p><p>If the economics work out, space-based solar could become the backbone of a truly global clean energy grid — delivering power to any point on Earth, day or night, regardless of weather or geography.</p>"
