    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1473341304170-971dccb5ac1e?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>For over a century, wireless power transmission was a laboratory curiosity — impressive in demonstrations but impractical at any useful distance. That's changing. Companies across the globe are now beaming usable amounts of electricity over tens of metres, and the technology is approaching commercial deployment.</p><p>The key breakthrough has been in metamaterial antennas — engineered surfaces that can focus electromagnetic energy into tight beams with minimal losses. Combined with advanced rectifying antennas (rectennas) that convert microwave energy back into electricity with over 90% efficiency, the practical barriers are falling fast.</p><p>Safety is a primary concern, and engineers have addressed it creatively. Laser curtain systems create an invisible safety boundary around the beam path. If anything — a bird, a person, a drone — breaks the curtain, the beam shuts off in milliseconds. The system restarts automatically once the path is clear.</p><p>Early applications focus on scenarios where wires are impractical: powering sensors on bridges and oil rigs, delivering electricity across rivers and ravines, and supplying remote telecommunications towers. In each case, the cost of wireless transmission is lower than running cables through difficult terrain.</p><p>The efficiency question is often raised: current systems deliver about 70-80% of the transmitted energy to the receiver over short distances, dropping to around 50% at longer ranges. That sounds wasteful, but when the alternative is diesel generators or no power at all, the calculus changes completely.</p><p>As the technology matures, expect to see it embedded in urban infrastructure — charging drones in flight, powering street furniture, and eventually delivering energy across city blocks without a single cable.</p>"
