    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1558346490-a72e53ae2d4f?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>In Wenatchee, Washington, something remarkable is happening at the bus stops. As passengers board and alight, the electric buses beneath them are silently charging — through the road surface itself, with no plugs, no cables, and no driver intervention.</p><p>The system uses inductive charging pads embedded in the tarmac at bus stops. When a bus pulls up and aligns with the pad, a magnetic field transfers energy through the few-inch gap between road and vehicle at rates up to 300 kilowatts. In the 5-10 minutes a bus typically spends at a stop, it can recover enough charge for several more miles of driving.</p><p>This 'opportunity charging' model eliminates the need for large, heavy batteries. Instead of carrying enough energy for an entire day's route, buses can carry smaller, lighter battery packs and top up continuously throughout their schedule. The result: lower vehicle costs, better energy efficiency, and routes that can run indefinitely without returning to a depot.</p><p>The technology isn't limited to buses. Several cities are piloting wireless charging for taxis at ranks, delivery vehicles at loading bays, and even passenger cars at traffic lights. South Korea has built a 12-kilometre stretch of highway with embedded charging coils that power vehicles as they drive.</p><p>Installation costs remain the main barrier. Cutting into road surfaces to embed charging hardware is expensive, and coordinating with utility companies to supply the necessary power adds complexity. But as electric vehicle adoption accelerates, the infrastructure investment looks increasingly justified.</p>"
