    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1620712943543-bcc4688e7485?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>In 1901, Nikola Tesla began construction of Wardenclyffe Tower on Long Island, New York. His vision was nothing less than a global wireless power and communication system — electricity and information transmitted through the Earth itself, available to anyone with a receiver. The project ran out of funding and the tower was demolished in 1917. For decades, it seemed like a brilliant man's most spectacular failure.</p><p>But Tesla wasn't wrong about the physics. He correctly identified electromagnetic resonance as the mechanism for wireless energy transfer. His demonstrations of lighting fluorescent tubes from across a room were genuine, reproducible, and ahead of their time by a century.</p><p>What Tesla lacked was the materials science and electronics to make the technology practical. Today's engineers have metamaterials, gallium nitride semiconductors, and computational tools that Tesla could never have imagined. These advances have turned his core insights into working products.</p><p>The parallels between Tesla's era and ours are striking. In the 1890s, the debate was between AC and DC power distribution. Tesla championed AC and won, enabling long-distance power transmission by wire. Today, the debate is between wired and wireless distribution for the 'last mile' — getting power from the grid to the device. And once again, Tesla's preferred approach is gaining ground.</p><p>Perhaps the most fitting tribute to Tesla is that his dream isn't being realised by a single inventor or company, but by a global community of engineers building on his principles. From charging pads in Norwegian ferry terminals to microwave beams in New Zealand to resonant coupling labs in MIT, the distributed wireless future Tesla envisioned is emerging — just not in the way he expected.</p>"
