    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1509390144018-eeaf65052242?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>In the mountainous regions of Nepal, Papua New Guinea, and rural Ghana, laying power lines is not just expensive — it's often physically impossible. Steep terrain, dense jungle, and river crossings make conventional grid extension prohibitively difficult. For the 770 million people worldwide who still lack electricity, the wire itself is the bottleneck.</p><p>Directed-energy power transmission offers a radical alternative. Instead of stringing cables across difficult terrain, a laser or microwave beam can deliver power line-of-sight from a generator to a receiver — leaping across valleys, rivers, and mountain passes that would stymie conventional infrastructure.</p><p>The physics is straightforward: a high-powered laser converts electricity to light, which travels through the air to a photovoltaic receiver that converts it back to electricity. Modern systems achieve end-to-end efficiencies of around 20-30% — low by grid standards, but transformative for communities that currently have no power at all.</p><p>Safety systems ensure the beam poses no danger to people or wildlife. Sensors continuously monitor the beam path, and the system shuts down instantly if anything enters the transmission corridor. The laser wavelengths used are also chosen to be eye-safe at the power densities involved.</p><p>Pilot projects are already underway. In one trial, a laser system delivered power across a 1.5-kilometre gap in mountainous terrain to a small village, providing enough electricity for lighting, phone charging, and a community refrigerator. For the villagers, it was the first reliable electricity they had ever experienced.</p>"
