    body: "<p>Look behind your desk. Count the cables. Phone charger, laptop power supply, monitor cable, speaker wire, lamp cord — the average home office has a dozen or more wires snaking across the floor. Now imagine they all disappeared.</p><p>Magnetic resonance coupling — the same technology that powers wireless phone chargers — is being scaled up to room-size. Researchers at multiple universities have demonstrated systems that can power any device within a 5-metre radius, regardless of its position or orientation in the room.</p><p>The system works by creating a magnetic field that resonates at a specific frequency throughout the room. Devices equipped with matching receiver coils absorb energy from the field, while objects that aren't tuned to the frequency — including human bodies — are unaffected.</p><p>Current prototypes can deliver around 50 watts at room scale, enough for phones, tablets, laptops, and LED lighting. Higher-power applications like televisions and kitchen appliances will require further development, but the roadmap is clear.</p><p>The design implications are profound. Furniture no longer needs to be positioned near outlets. Lighting can be placed anywhere without wiring. Rooms become truly flexible spaces, reconfigurable at will. Architects are already designing 'wireless-ready' buildings with resonance infrastructure built into walls and ceilings.</p><p>The biggest remaining challenge is standardisation. Without a universal wireless power standard, each manufacturer's devices would need their own ecosystem. Industry bodies are working to prevent this fragmentation, but the history of technology standards suggests the process will be slow.</p>"
