    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1507413245164-6160d8298b31?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>It sounds like an urban myth, but it's actually true: pressing your car's wireless key fob against your head can extend its range by several metres. The trick has been tested repeatedly by physicists and car enthusiasts alike, and the results are consistent.</p><p>The explanation lies in the way radio waves interact with the human body. Your key fob transmits a weak radio signal at around 315 or 433 MHz. At these frequencies, your body — which is mostly water — acts as a reasonably effective antenna, amplifying and redirecting the signal.</p><p>When you hold the fob against your skull, the signal couples into the water-rich tissues of your head, which effectively increases the antenna size. The larger antenna produces a stronger, more focused signal in the direction you're facing. It's not magic — it's basic antenna theory.</p><p>The effect is modest but real: typically extending the useful range by 30-50%. In a car park where you're right at the edge of your fob's range, that extra boost can make the difference between a satisfying chirp and a frustrating walk back towards your car.</p><p>Interestingly, the same principle works with a water bottle. Holding the fob against a full water bottle produces a similar range extension. This confirms that it's the dielectric properties of water, not anything special about the human body, that creates the effect.</p>"
