    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1462331940025-496dfbfc7564?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>The universe exists in an extraordinary state of balance. Stars burn steadily for billions of years, galaxies maintain their spiral structure across cosmic time, and the fundamental constants of physics appear fine-tuned to permit the existence of complex matter. But what maintains this equilibrium?</p><p>At the stellar scale, the answer is a tug of war between gravity and radiation pressure. A star's enormous mass wants to collapse inward, but the nuclear fusion reactions in its core generate outward pressure that exactly counterbalances gravity. When the fuel runs out, the balance tips — and the star either fades gently into a white dwarf or explodes spectacularly as a supernova.</p><p>At the cosmic scale, the balance is between gravity — which tries to pull all matter together — and dark energy, which pushes the universe apart. Current measurements show that dark energy is winning: the expansion of the universe is accelerating, and galaxies are moving apart faster and faster.</p><p>The most puzzling balance is in the fundamental constants themselves. If the strong nuclear force were just 2% weaker, no elements heavier than hydrogen would exist. If gravity were slightly stronger, stars would burn through their fuel in millions of years instead of billions, leaving no time for complex life to evolve.</p><p>Whether this fine-tuning reflects a deeper physical principle, a multiverse of different constants, or something else entirely remains one of the greatest open questions in physics. The universe's balance, it seems, is both precise and profoundly mysterious.</p>"
