    slug: "save-great-barrier-reef",
    title: "How Can We Save the Great Barrier Reef?",
    topic: "Environment",
    date: "20 Jan 2026",
    readTime: "7 min read",
    author: "Dr. Emma Richards",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1582967788606-a171c1080cb0?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>The Great Barrier Reef — the largest living structure on Earth, visible from space — is in crisis. Mass bleaching events in 2016, 2017, 2020, and 2022 have killed significant portions of the reef's coral, driven by marine heatwaves linked to climate change.</p><p>But Australian scientists aren't giving up. A remarkable array of interventions is being deployed, from the high-tech to the surprisingly simple.</p><p>Cloud brightening is one of the most ambitious approaches. Researchers are testing turbines that spray ultra-fine sea salt particles into low-lying clouds above the reef. The salt crystals make the clouds more reflective, bouncing more sunlight back into space and cooling the water below by a fraction of a degree. In the razor-thin margins between survival and bleaching, that fraction matters.</p><p>Selective breeding is another strategy. Scientists have identified corals that naturally tolerate higher temperatures and are crossbreeding them to create heat-resistant strains. These 'super corals' are being propagated in underwater nurseries and transplanted onto damaged sections of reef.</p><p>Perhaps the simplest intervention is also one of the most effective: controlling crown-of-thorns starfish. These voracious predators eat coral tissue and can devastate reef sections during population explosions. Targeted injection programs kill individual starfish while leaving other marine life unharmed.</p><p>None of these interventions can save the reef without addressing the root cause: rising ocean temperatures driven by greenhouse gas emissions. But they can buy time — keeping the reef alive long enough for humanity to get its carbon emissions under control.</p>"
