    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1544551763-46a013bb70d5?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>In 2018, a cleaner wrasse — a small tropical fish — appeared to pass the mirror test, a classic experiment used to assess self-awareness in animals. The fish noticed a coloured mark on its body that was only visible in a mirror, then tried to scrape the mark off against a hard surface. The result stunned the scientific community and reignited fierce debate about what self-awareness really means.</p><p>The mirror test was developed in 1970 by psychologist Gordon Gallup Jr. An animal that recognises its own reflection — rather than treating it as another individual — is said to have self-recognition, a key component of self-awareness. Previously, only great apes, elephants, dolphins, and magpies had passed.</p><p>Critics argued that the fish's behaviour could be explained without invoking self-awareness. Perhaps the wrasse was simply bothered by the physical sensation of the mark and would have tried to remove it regardless of the mirror. Perhaps it had learned to use the mirror as a tool without understanding that the reflection was itself.</p><p>Subsequent experiments have strengthened the case. Fish that had never seen a mark in a mirror didn't try to remove it. Fish without marks didn't scrape themselves after seeing the mirror. The pattern of behaviour closely matched what's seen in chimpanzees and dolphins.</p><p>If fish are self-aware, even in a limited sense, it has profound implications for how we think about consciousness. It suggests that self-recognition may not require a large brain or complex social structure — it may be a more basic feature of nervous systems than we previously imagined.</p>"
