    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516979187457-637abb4f9353?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>For some people, silence is blissful — a rare commodity in a noisy world. For others, it's genuinely distressing: the absence of sound creates anxiety, discomfort, and an urgent need to fill the void. Neuroscience is beginning to explain why.</p><p>The brain, it turns out, is not designed for silence. In the absence of external input, the auditory cortex doesn't go quiet — it becomes more active, generating its own signals. This is why prolonged silence often produces phantom sounds: ringing, humming, or the sensation of hearing your own heartbeat.</p><p>For people prone to anxiety, this internal amplification can be threatening. In evolutionary terms, silence often preceded danger — a forest going quiet meant a predator was near. Some researchers believe that discomfort with silence is a vestige of this ancient survival mechanism, still active in brains that interpret quiet as a warning signal.</p><p>Studies in anechoic chambers — rooms engineered to absorb virtually all sound — reveal just how poorly humans tolerate true silence. Most people become uncomfortable within minutes. Some report dizziness, nausea, and even hallucinations. The longest anyone has voluntarily stayed in an anechoic chamber is around 45 minutes.</p><p>Personality plays a role too. Extroverts tend to find silence more aversive than introverts, consistent with theories that extroversion is partly driven by a need for external stimulation. People with a history of trauma may also find silence triggering, as it removes the background noise that serves as an unconscious reassurance of safety.</p>"
