    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1532187863486-abf9dbad1b69?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>A listener named Namrata noticed something puzzling: she tans more in Boston than in India, despite India being closer to the equator. The explanation involves a surprising mix of atmospheric science, geography, and skin biology.</p><p>UV intensity at ground level depends on far more than latitude. Altitude matters — UV increases by about 10% for every 1,000 metres of elevation. Humidity matters — water vapour absorbs some UV wavelengths. Ozone thickness matters — the ozone layer is thinner at higher latitudes, counterintuitively allowing more UV through in some conditions.</p><p>Boston sits at 42°N latitude with relatively low humidity in summer and a thinner ozone layer than tropical regions. India's major cities, while closer to the equator, often have high humidity and pollution that scatter and absorb UV before it reaches the ground.</p><p>Skin response also varies. Melanin — the pigment that darkens skin — is produced in response to UV-B radiation specifically. If you move from a high-UV-B environment to a lower one, your baseline melanin production decreases. When you then encounter concentrated UV-B exposure (say, a sunny Boston summer), the contrast triggers a stronger tanning response.</p><p>Time of year, time of day, and even the reflectivity of your surroundings play roles. Snow reflects up to 80% of UV radiation, effectively doubling your exposure. Sand reflects about 15%. Water reflects 10%. The geometry of UV exposure is more complex than simply measuring distance from the equator.</p>"
