    author: "Dr. Rachel Torres",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1534996858221-380b92700493?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>One-third of humanity can no longer see the Milky Way. Light pollution — the brightening of the night sky by artificial sources — has grown so severe that for most city dwellers, the stars have effectively disappeared. And the problem is getting worse, with global light emissions increasing by roughly 2% per year.</p><p>The consequences extend far beyond aesthetics. Light pollution disrupts ecosystems on a massive scale. Sea turtle hatchlings, guided by moonlight, crawl towards streetlights instead of the ocean. Migrating birds become disoriented by illuminated buildings. Insects — whose populations have declined dramatically — are drawn to lights where they exhaust themselves and die.</p><p>For humans, artificial light at night suppresses melatonin production, disrupting circadian rhythms and increasing risks of sleep disorders, obesity, and certain cancers. The World Health Organisation has classified night-shift work as a probable carcinogen, partly due to light exposure.</p><p>The solutions are straightforward and cost-effective. Shielded light fixtures that direct light downward instead of skyward can reduce light pollution by 50% or more while actually improving visibility at ground level. Warm-coloured LEDs (2700K or lower) scatter less in the atmosphere than the blue-white LEDs that many cities have installed. Motion sensors and timers can eliminate lighting when nobody is around to use it.</p><p>Several jurisdictions have enacted dark-sky legislation, and the International Dark-Sky Association certifies communities that meet strict lighting standards. These efforts have produced striking results: in protected areas, the Milky Way is visible again for the first time in decades.</p>"
