  {
    slug: "what-is-dark-matter",
    title: "What Is Dark Matter?",
    topic: "Cosmology",
    date: "15 Jul 2025",
    readTime: "9 min read",
    author: "Prof. Elena Volkov",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1464802686167-b939a6910659?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>Roughly 27% of the universe is made of a substance that has never been directly detected, doesn't emit or absorb light, and interacts with ordinary matter only through gravity. We call it dark matter, and its nature is one of the biggest unsolved problems in physics.</p><p>The evidence for dark matter is overwhelming. Galaxies rotate too fast — their stars should fly apart based on the gravity of visible matter alone. Galaxy clusters are held together by far more mass than we can see. The cosmic microwave background radiation shows patterns that can only be explained by a universe with five times more dark matter than ordinary matter.</p><p>The leading candidate is a yet-undiscovered subatomic particle — a Weakly Interacting Massive Particle (WIMP) that experiences gravity and possibly the weak nuclear force, but not electromagnetism or the strong force. This would explain why dark matter is invisible: it doesn't interact with photons.</p><p>Detectors deep underground — shielded from cosmic rays by kilometres of rock — are searching for the rare collision between a WIMP and an ordinary atom. So far, decades of searching have produced no confirmed detection, placing ever-tighter constraints on what WIMPs can be.</p><p>Alternative theories propose that dark matter isn't a particle at all. Modified gravity theories (MOND) suggest that our understanding of gravity is incomplete at galactic scales. Others propose dark matter is made of primordial black holes formed in the early universe. The truth may be stranger than any current theory imagines.</p>"
  },
  {
    slug: "wounds-itch-healing",
    title: "Why Do Wounds Itch When They Heal?",
    topic: "Medicine",
    date: "8 Jul 2025",
    readTime: "4 min read",
    author: "Dr. Sarah Mitchell",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1584515933487-779824d29309?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>That maddening itch around a healing wound is one of the most universal human experiences — and one of the most poorly understood. Far from being a nuisance, the itch is an integral part of the healing process, driven by the same chemical signals that repair damaged tissue.</p><p>When skin is wounded, the body launches an inflammatory response. Immune cells flood the area, releasing histamine — the same molecule responsible for allergic itching. Histamine dilates blood vessels, increases blood flow to the wound, and stimulates nerve endings. The resulting itch sensation is essentially a side effect of the healing process.</p><p>As the wound closes, new skin cells grow across the gap. These cells produce neuropeptides — small signalling molecules that stimulate the growth of new nerve endings in the healing tissue. The fresh nerve endings are hypersensitive, firing at lower thresholds than mature nerves. This hypersensitivity amplifies the itch signal.</p><p>Collagen deposition adds another layer. As scar tissue forms, collagen fibres contract and pull on surrounding skin, mechanically stimulating nerve endings and producing both itch and tightness.</p><p>Scratching, unfortunately, is counterproductive. It damages the fragile new tissue, potentially reopening the wound and restarting the inflammatory cycle. The body's signal to pay attention to the healing wound is at odds with the appropriate response, which is to leave it alone. It's one of evolution's less elegant design choices.</p>"
  },
  {
    slug: "octopus-intelligence",
    title: "How Smart Are Octopuses?",
    topic: "Animal Cognition",
    date: "1 Jul 2025",
    readTime: "6 min read",
    author: "Dr. Peter Godfrey-Smith",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1545671913-b89d1b6a0c10?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>An octopus at the Seattle Aquarium learned to unscrew jars to get food inside. Another at a New Zealand aquarium repeatedly short-circuited a light above its tank by squirting water at the bulb. A third was caught on security cameras leaving its tank at night, crossing the floor to a neighbouring tank to eat fish, and returning to its own tank before morning. These aren't just anecdotes — they're data points in a growing body of evidence for remarkable intelligence in a creature profoundly unlike us.</p><p>Octopuses have roughly 500 million neurons — comparable to a dog — but distributed radically differently. Two-thirds of their neurons are in their arms, not their brain. Each arm can taste, touch, and make independent decisions. An octopus is less like a centralised brain with limbs and more like a distributed intelligence — eight semi-autonomous agents coordinated by a central processor.</p><p>In laboratory tests, octopuses navigate complex mazes, distinguish shapes and patterns, use tools (carrying coconut shells as portable shelters), and learn by watching other octopuses — a form of social learning once thought to require a much larger brain.</p><p>Perhaps most intriguingly, octopuses appear to play. Individuals have been observed blowing empty pill bottles back and forth in the current of their tank, seemingly for no purpose other than entertainment. Play is considered a hallmark of intelligence in mammals, and its presence in octopuses suggests it may arise from more fundamental neural principles.</p><p>The octopus lineage diverged from ours over 500 million years ago. Whatever intelligence they possess evolved completely independently from our own. They represent the closest thing to an alien mind that exists on Earth.</p>"
  },
  {
    slug: "forests-talk",
    title: "Can Forests Really Talk to Each Other?",
    topic: "Mycology",
    date: "24 Jun 2025",
    readTime: "7 min read",
    author: "Prof. Suzanne Forest",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1518531933037-91b2f5f229cc?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>Beneath every forest floor lies a hidden network of extraordinary complexity. Mycorrhizal fungi — threadlike organisms too fine to see with the naked eye — form connections between the roots of nearly every tree and plant. Through this 'Wood Wide Web,' trees exchange resources, share information, and support their offspring in ways that challenge our understanding of plant life.</p><p>The relationship is mutualistic. Trees provide fungi with sugars produced by photosynthesis. In return, fungal networks extend the tree's effective root system by orders of magnitude, accessing water and mineral nutrients that roots alone could never reach. A single tree can be connected to hundreds of others through dozens of fungal species.</p><p>Carbon tracking experiments have revealed that trees share resources through the network. A shaded seedling receives carbon from a sunlit neighbour. A tree infested with bark beetles dumps its carbon reserves into the network before dying. Mother trees preferentially channel nutrients to their own seedlings, suggesting a form of kin recognition.</p><p>Defensive signalling also travels through the network. When a Douglas fir is attacked by budworms, neighbouring trees connected by mycorrhizal fungi upregulate their own defensive chemicals — even before any budworms reach them. The fungal network appears to transmit a warning signal.</p><p>The implications for forestry are significant. Clear-cutting destroys the fungal network, leaving replanted seedlings without the support system they need. Selective logging that preserves hub trees — large, well-connected individuals — maintains the network and dramatically improves regeneration rates.</p>"
  },
  {
    slug: "spicy-food-burns",
    title: "Why Does Spicy Food Burn?",
    topic: "Chemistry",
    date: "17 Jun 2025",
    readTime: "4 min read",
    author: "Dr. Raj Patel",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1563379926898-05f4575a45d8?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>Bite into a raw chilli pepper and your mouth erupts in burning pain. But there's no actual heat, no tissue damage, and no chemical burn. The sensation is an elaborate deception — your brain has been tricked into believing something that isn't happening.</p><p>The active molecule is capsaicin, found in the placental tissue of chilli peppers (the white pith, not the seeds). Capsaicin binds to TRPV1 receptors on sensory nerve endings — the same receptors that detect temperatures above 43°C. By activating these receptors, capsaicin produces the identical neural signal as genuine heat. Your brain receives a 'this is hot' message and responds accordingly: pain, sweating, flushing, and tears.</p><p>The evolutionary purpose is defensive. Chilli plants produce capsaicin to deter mammals from eating their fruit. Mammalian teeth crush seeds, destroying them. Birds, however, lack TRPV1 receptors and are immune to capsaicin — they eat the fruit, fly away, and deposit the seeds intact in their droppings, far from the parent plant.</p><p>Humans are the exception: we've learned to enjoy the sensation. The pain triggers endorphin release — the body's natural painkillers — producing a mild euphoria that many people find addictive. Repeated exposure desensitises the TRPV1 receptors, increasing tolerance and allowing chilli enthusiasts to consume increasingly potent peppers.</p><p>Capsaicin is fat-soluble, not water-soluble, which is why water doesn't help when your mouth is burning. Milk, yoghurt, or any fat-containing food will dissolve the capsaicin and wash it away from the receptors. This is why many spicy cuisines are served with dairy accompaniments.</p>"
  },
  {
    slug: "communicate-with-aliens",
    title: "Could We Ever Communicate With Aliens?",
    topic: "Astrobiology",
    date: "10 Jun 2025",
    readTime: "8 min read",
    author: "Dr. Jill Tarter",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1454789548928-9efd52dc4031?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>Since 1960, the Search for Extraterrestrial Intelligence (SETI) has been scanning the skies for artificial signals from other civilisations. So far, the search has found nothing confirmed. But the question of how we would communicate with an alien intelligence — if we found one — is as fascinating as the search itself.</p><p>The first challenge is detection. Any signal from another star system would take years, decades, or millennia to arrive. A signal from the nearest star, Proxima Centauri, would take 4.24 years at the speed of light. A signal from across the galaxy would take 100,000 years. Communication would be a monologue, not a conversation.</p><p>The second challenge is comprehension. We can't assume aliens share any of our sensory modalities, cognitive frameworks, or cultural references. Mathematics is often proposed as a universal language — the properties of prime numbers, for instance, are the same everywhere in the universe. But even mathematical communication requires shared assumptions about notation and encoding.</p><p>Some scientists have proposed sending physical artefacts rather than signals. The Pioneer plaques and the Voyager Golden Records — currently drifting through interstellar space — carry images, sounds, and symbolic information intended for alien finders. Whether any intelligence could decode them without extensive context is debatable.</p><p>The most contentious question is whether we should be trying to communicate at all. Active SETI — deliberately broadcasting signals toward promising star systems — has vocal critics who argue that advertising our existence to unknown intelligences is reckless. Proponents counter that our television and radar signals have already been leaking into space for decades. The debate remains unresolved.</p>"
  },
  {
    slug: "brain-during-meditation",
    title: "What Happens to Your Brain During Meditation?",
    topic: "Neuroscience",
    date: "3 Jun 2025",
    readTime: "6 min read",
    author: "Dr. Richard Davidson",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1506126613408-eca07ce68773?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>Meditation was once dismissed by neuroscience as a subjective practice with no measurable biological effects. That view has been thoroughly overturned. MRI studies now show that regular meditation physically changes the brain's structure and function in measurable, replicable ways.</p><p>The most consistent finding is increased thickness of the prefrontal cortex — the brain region responsible for executive function, decision-making, and emotional regulation. Experienced meditators show cortical thickening in areas associated with attention and sensory processing, even compared to age-matched controls. In a sense, meditation appears to slow or reverse the cortical thinning that normally occurs with ageing.</p><p>The amygdala — the brain's fear and threat-detection centre — shows reduced volume and reactivity in regular meditators. This correlates with self-reported decreases in anxiety and stress. The change is not just a temporary calming effect; it persists between meditation sessions, suggesting structural remodelling.</p><p>The default mode network (DMN) — a set of brain regions active during mind-wandering, daydreaming, and self-referential thought — is modulated by meditation. In novice meditators, the DMN activates strongly during meditation. In experienced practitioners, DMN activity decreases significantly, correlating with reports of reduced mental chatter and greater present-moment awareness.</p><p>How much meditation is needed to produce these changes? Studies suggest measurable effects begin after as little as eight weeks of regular practice (about 30 minutes per day). More intensive practice produces more pronounced changes. The relationship between meditation hours and brain changes appears to be roughly linear — more practice, more change — at least up to the thousands of hours logged by experienced practitioners.</p>"
  },
  {
    slug: "firefly-synchronisation",
    title: "How Do Fireflies Synchronise Their Flashing?",
    topic: "Biology",
    date: "27 May 2025",
    readTime: "5 min read",
    author: "Dr. Steven Strogatz",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1470058869958-2a77bde3e86a?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>In the mangrove forests of Southeast Asia, thousands of fireflies flash in perfect synchrony — entire riverbanks blinking on and off in unison, like strings of Christmas lights. The display is breathtaking, and for decades, scientists couldn't explain how it worked. There's no conductor, no leader, no central clock. How do thousands of independent insects coordinate their behaviour so precisely?</p><p>The answer is beautifully simple: each firefly adjusts its own rhythm based on the flashes it sees from its neighbours. If a firefly sees a flash slightly before its own, it speeds up slightly. If it sees a flash slightly after, it slows down. Over many cycles, these tiny adjustments accumulate until the entire population locks into synchrony.</p><p>This process — coupled oscillator synchronisation — is described by elegant mathematics first formalised by Art Winfree and Yoshiki Kuramoto. The Kuramoto model shows that synchronisation is a phase transition: below a critical coupling strength, oscillators remain disordered; above it, they spontaneously lock together.</p><p>The same mathematics describes phenomena across vastly different scales. Heart pacemaker cells synchronise their firing through electrical coupling. Audiences clapping in unison follow the same dynamics. Power grid generators must maintain synchronous rotation to deliver stable electricity. Even the orbit-orbit resonances of planetary moons follow related principles.</p><p>For the fireflies themselves, synchronisation serves a reproductive purpose. Females prefer synchronous males, possibly because synchrony is an honest signal of health and cognitive function — only fit fireflies can keep perfect time. The mathematics of synchronisation, it turns out, is also the mathematics of sexual selection.</p>"
  },
  {
    slug: "why-glass-transparent",
    title: "Why Is Glass Transparent?",
    topic: "Materials Science",
    date: "20 May 2025",
    readTime: "5 min read",
    author: "Prof. Richard Feynman Jr.",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1494438639946-1ebd1d20bf85?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>Glass is a solid. Light passes right through it. This seems paradoxical — after all, light doesn't pass through most solids. A block of iron, a piece of wood, a sheet of paper: all are opaque. What makes glass different?</p><p>The answer lies in quantum mechanics, specifically in the energy gaps between electron states in the material's atoms. When a photon of visible light hits an atom, it can only be absorbed if its energy exactly matches the gap between two electron energy levels. If no gap matches, the photon passes through as if the atom weren't there.</p><p>In metals, electrons are delocalised — they move freely throughout the material in a 'sea' of electrons. These free electrons can absorb photons of any energy, which is why metals are opaque (and also why they're electrically conductive and reflective).</p><p>In glass (silicon dioxide), all electrons are tightly bound in covalent bonds between silicon and oxygen atoms. The energy gap between the ground state and the first excited state is larger than the energy of any visible-light photon. Visible photons simply don't have enough energy to be absorbed, so they pass through. Ultraviolet photons, which have higher energy, are absorbed — which is why glass blocks UV light.</p><p>The disorder of glass is also important. In a crystal, atoms are arranged in a regular lattice that can scatter light at specific angles (producing reflections and refractions). In glass, the amorphous structure lacks long-range order, producing less scattering and greater transparency. It's the combination of quantum mechanical transparency and structural disorder that makes glass the uniquely useful material it is.</p>"
  },
  {
    slug: "crispr-genetic-diseases",
    title: "Can CRISPR Cure Genetic Diseases?",
    topic: "Genetics",
    date: "13 May 2025",
    readTime: "8 min read",
    author: "Prof. Jennifer Liu",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1628595351029-c2bf17511435?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>In December 2023, the FDA approved Casgevy — the first CRISPR-based gene therapy — for the treatment of sickle cell disease. Patients who previously suffered debilitating pain crises now produce healthy red blood cells. The era of gene editing as medicine has officially begun.</p><p>CRISPR-Cas9 works like molecular scissors. A guide RNA molecule directs the Cas9 enzyme to a specific location in the genome, where it cuts both strands of DNA. The cell's repair machinery then either disables the targeted gene or, if a template is provided, replaces it with a corrected version.</p><p>The potential applications are staggering. Over 6,000 human diseases are caused by mutations in single genes — cystic fibrosis, Huntington's disease, muscular dystrophy, and many forms of blindness among them. In principle, CRISPR could correct any of these by fixing the underlying mutation.</p><p>But significant challenges remain. Off-target edits — cuts at unintended locations in the genome — could potentially cause cancer or other problems. Delivery is difficult: getting CRISPR components into the right cells in a living patient requires sophisticated viral vectors or nanoparticle carriers. And for diseases affecting the brain, the blood-brain barrier presents an additional obstacle.</p><p>The ethical boundaries are also being tested. Germline editing — changing DNA that would be passed to future generations — is technically possible but widely considered premature. The case of He Jiankui, who edited human embryos in 2018 and was subsequently imprisoned, demonstrated both the power of the technology and the consequences of using it irresponsibly.</p><p>Most researchers believe that within a decade, CRISPR therapies will be available for dozens of genetic conditions. The technology is moving from 'can we do this?' to 'how do we do this safely, fairly, and affordably?'</p>"
  },
  {
    slug: "deja-vu",
    title: "What Causes D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu?",
    topic: "Psychology",
    date: "6 May 2025",
    readTime: "5 min read",
    author: "Dr. Anne Cleary",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1507003211169-0a1dd7228f2d?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>You walk into a room you've never visited before, and suddenly you're overwhelmed by the sensation that you've been here before — that you've lived this exact moment, in this exact place, with these exact words being spoken. The feeling is vivid, disorienting, and usually fleeting. This is deja vu, and about two-thirds of people experience it at some point in their lives.</p><p>The leading scientific explanation involves a glitch in memory processing. Normally, new experiences are first processed by the perirhinal cortex (which handles familiarity) and the hippocampus (which handles recollection) simultaneously. Deja vu may occur when the familiarity signal fires without the corresponding recollection — your brain tags the experience as 'known' before it's finished recording it as 'new.'</p><p>Supporting this theory, deja vu is more common in people with temporal lobe epilepsy, where electrical disturbances in the memory-processing regions can trigger intense and prolonged episodes. Some patients experience deja vu as an aura before seizures, confirming the link to temporal lobe activity.</p><p>Another theory proposes that deja vu results from pattern matching. Your brain constantly compares current experiences to stored memories, looking for similarities. If the current scene closely matches a memory — perhaps a room with similar layout to one you visited years ago — the match can trigger a familiarity signal even though the specific experience is new.</p><p>Age affects deja vu frequency. It peaks in young adults (late teens to mid-twenties) and declines with age. This pattern is consistent with the memory-glitch theory: younger brains are faster at processing and more prone to timing mismatches, while older brains process more slowly but more synchronously.</p>"
  },
  {
    slug: "vaccines-immune-system",
    title: "How Do Vaccines Train Your Immune System?",
    topic: "Immunology",
    date: "29 Apr 2025",
    readTime: "6 min read",
    author: "Dr. Paul Offit",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1584308666744-24d5c474f2ae?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>Your immune system is a learning machine. Every pathogen it encounters is analysed, catalogued, and remembered — sometimes for decades. Vaccines exploit this learning capacity by presenting the immune system with a harmless preview of a dangerous pathogen, allowing it to prepare defences in advance.</p><p>The process begins when a vaccine introduces antigens — molecules from the pathogen's surface — into the body. These can be inactivated virus particles, purified proteins, or (in the case of mRNA vaccines) instructions for your cells to produce the antigens themselves.</p><p>Dendritic cells — the immune system's sentinels — detect the antigens and present them to T-cells and B-cells in the lymph nodes. This triggers a multi-phase response: B-cells produce antibodies that can neutralise the pathogen, while T-cells learn to recognise and destroy infected cells.</p><p>The critical step is memory cell formation. After the initial response subsides, a population of long-lived memory B-cells and memory T-cells remains in the body. These cells can persist for years or decades, maintaining a molecular 'wanted poster' for the pathogen. If the real pathogen ever appears, the memory cells activate immediately, producing a response that's faster, stronger, and more targeted than the first.</p><p>This is why vaccination works: the first exposure happens under controlled conditions, with no risk of disease. By the time the real pathogen arrives, the immune system has already rehearsed its response and can eliminate the threat before symptoms develop.</p>"
  },
  {
    slug: "animals-glow-dark",
    title: "Why Do Some Animals Glow in the Dark?",
    topic: "Marine Biology",
    date: "22 Apr 2025",
    readTime: "6 min read",
    author: "Dr. Edith Widder",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1551085254-e96b210db58a?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>In the deep ocean — below 200 metres, where sunlight never reaches — the most common form of communication is light. An estimated 76% of deep-sea creatures produce bioluminescence, making it the most widespread form of biological signalling on Earth.</p><p>Bioluminescence is produced by a chemical reaction between a light-emitting molecule (luciferin) and an enzyme (luciferase). The reaction converts chemical energy directly into light with remarkable efficiency — nearly 100% of the energy becomes photons, compared to about 5% for an incandescent bulb.</p><p>The uses of bioluminescence are as diverse as the animals that produce it. Anglerfish dangle a glowing lure above their mouths to attract prey. Vampire squid eject clouds of luminescent mucus to confuse predators. Cookie-cutter sharks use glowing bellies for counter-illumination — matching the faint light from above to erase their silhouette from below.</p><p>Some of the most spectacular displays serve reproductive purposes. Ostracods — tiny crustaceans — produce elaborate patterns of bioluminescent pulses to attract mates, creating underwater light shows visible to divers. Each species has a distinct flash pattern, preventing cross-species confusion.</p><p>Bioluminescence has evolved independently at least 50 times across the tree of life, appearing in bacteria, fungi, jellyfish, fish, insects, and worms. This extraordinary convergence suggests that producing light is such a powerful adaptation that evolution has invented it again and again, each time from different molecular starting points.</p>"
  },
  {
    slug: "fungi-save-planet",
    title: "Could Fungi Save the Planet?",
    topic: "Ecology",
    date: "15 Apr 2025",
    readTime: "7 min read",
    author: "Dr. Merlin Sheldrake",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1504700610630-ac6aba3536d3?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>Fungi are the unsung heroes of Earth's ecosystems. They decompose dead matter, cycle nutrients, form symbioses with 90% of plant species, and maintain the soil structure that supports terrestrial life. Now, scientists are discovering that fungi could help solve some of humanity's most pressing environmental problems.</p><p>Mycoremediation — using fungi to clean up pollution — is one of the most promising applications. Certain species of oyster mushroom can break down petroleum hydrocarbons, turning contaminated soil into clean compost. Others can accumulate heavy metals from polluted water, effectively filtering toxic waste through a living organism.</p><p>Mycelium — the threadlike root structure of fungi — is being developed as a sustainable material. Companies are growing mycelium into packaging, building insulation, leather alternatives, and even structural materials. The process requires only agricultural waste as feedstock and produces no synthetic chemicals.</p><p>Carbon sequestration through mycorrhizal fungi could be significant at global scale. These fungi store an estimated 13 gigatonnes of carbon in the soil each year — roughly equivalent to a third of global fossil fuel emissions. Farming practices that support mycorrhizal networks (reduced tillage, cover cropping, diverse rotations) could increase this natural carbon sink.</p><p>Fungi are also yielding new medicines. Penicillin — still the world's most important antibiotic — came from a fungus. Cyclosporine, the immunosuppressant that made organ transplantation possible, came from a soil fungus. Psilocybin, produced by certain mushrooms, is showing remarkable efficacy in treating depression, PTSD, and addiction in clinical trials.</p><p>Mycologists estimate that we've identified only about 5% of the world's fungal species. The remaining 95% represent an almost untapped reservoir of biological solutions to human problems.</p>"
  },
  {
    slug: "gravity-bends-light",
    title: "How Does Gravity Bend Light?",
    topic: "Physics",
    date: "8 Apr 2025",
    readTime: "7 min read",
    author: "Prof. Arthur Eddington III",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1444703686981-a3abbc4d4fe3?w=480&h=270&fit=crop",
    body: "<p>In 1915, Albert Einstein published his general theory of relativity, which made a startling prediction: massive objects don't just attract other masses — they bend the fabric of spacetime itself. Light, travelling through curved spacetime, follows curved paths. Gravity doesn't pull light; it curves the space through which light travels.</p><p>The prediction was confirmed spectacularly in 1919 by Arthur Eddington, who observed stars near the Sun during a total solar eclipse. Stars that should have been hidden behind the Sun were visible — their light had been bent around the Sun's mass, shifting their apparent positions on the sky. Einstein became a global celebrity overnight.</p><p>Today, gravitational lensing is one of the most powerful tools in astronomy. When light from a distant galaxy passes near a massive foreground object — a galaxy cluster, for instance — the intervening mass acts as a natural magnifying glass. The background galaxy's light is bent, amplified, and sometimes split into multiple images.</p><p>Strong lensing produces dramatic arcs and rings of light — Einstein rings — that are among the most beautiful objects in astronomy. Weak lensing, a subtler effect, distorts the shapes of background galaxies slightly, allowing astronomers to map the distribution of dark matter (which bends light even though it's invisible).</p><p>Microlensing occurs when a compact object — a star or a planet — passes in front of a background star. The brief brightening that results has been used to discover exoplanets too faint to detect by any other method. Several Earth-mass planets in our galaxy have been found this way.</p><p>From a confirmed prediction of general relativity to a workhorse technique of modern astronomy, gravitational lensing demonstrates how a single theoretical insight can transform our ability to see the universe.</p>"
  }
